The defendant Tu M Tran was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Intent. Contribute/Delinquency Child, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 948.40(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defense counsel, attorney Eichenlaub, objects and places reasons on the record.  Attorney Levine, joins in co-defense objection.  Court DENIES State's motion for adjournment.

MOTION TO ALLOW OTHER ACTS EVIDENCE:  
Court issued tentative rulings as the Other Acts Evidence.  After hearing defense arguments and statements from State, courts DENIES and GRANTS some of the Other Acts Evidence, which were placed on the record.

State to call 9 witnesses, and defense 2-3.  Parties addressed convictions that are relevant to credibility as to the defendants and witnesses.  All witnesses have been subpoenaed.
